WEBVTT

00:08.029 --> 00:10.290
<i>Previously,</i>
<i>on Marvel's</i> Runaways...

00:10.290 --> 00:12.920
<i>As soon as I decrypt
that data, we'll have that tape,</i>

00:12.920 --> 00:15.210
undeniable proof that
our parents are killers.

00:15.210 --> 00:17.010
<i>How'd you guess
my mom's passcode?</i>

00:17.010 --> 00:18.430
I got lucky, I guess.

00:18.430 --> 00:20.060
Really lucky.

00:20.060 --> 00:22.020
What should I do about the fact

00:22.020 --> 00:25.020
that my wife is sleeping
with another man?

00:25.020 --> 00:26.360
Robert...

00:26.360 --> 00:28.280
- ‐ Oh!
- ‐

00:29.370 --> 00:31.330
‐
‐ No!

00:32.409 --> 00:33.880
Jonah can help.

00:33.880 --> 00:35.840
Oh, he's got a cure
for brain cancer?

00:35.840 --> 00:39.300
It's an experimental
immunotherapy developed from the DNA

00:39.300 --> 00:41.430
<i>of someone with an extraordinary
immune system.</i>

00:41.430 --> 00:44.060
Never felt better.
I've got a new lease on life,

00:44.060 --> 00:46.230
and a beautiful wife
who loves me.

00:46.230 --> 00:47.820
What more could a man want?

00:47.820 --> 00:49.620
I guess going Ultra wasn't for me.

00:49.620 --> 00:50.780
You went Ultra.

00:52.290 --> 00:53.830
You just didn't know it.

00:53.830 --> 00:55.750
<i>Frank should have</i>
<i>no memory of Jonah.</i>

00:55.750 --> 00:58.170
I messed up, big time.

00:58.170 --> 00:59.640
<i>Molly was in the basement.</i>

00:59.640 --> 01:01.220
I think she saw everything.

01:05.940 --> 01:08.110
That wraps it up for today.

01:08.110 --> 01:10.620
Papers due on my desk
by 3:00 p.m. tomorrow.

01:10.620 --> 01:11.990
Thank you.

01:11.990 --> 01:15.790
‐
‐

01:20.300 --> 01:22.350
Dude, have you seen
<i>Reservoir Dogs</i> yet?

01:22.350 --> 01:25.020
Oh, my God,
it was so good.

01:29.360 --> 01:31.700
You know, you're watching
the key to time travel.

01:33.620 --> 01:35.000
You're kidding, right?

01:36.080 --> 01:37.340
About time travel?

01:38.420 --> 01:40.680
No, that line. It's awful.

01:42.680 --> 01:44.890
That's not a line.
I saw your book

01:44.890 --> 01:47.860
and took you for someone
with a serious interest.

01:47.860 --> 01:49.190
My mistake.

01:51.610 --> 01:53.410
No, I'm interested...

01:54.830 --> 01:56.670
in time travel.

01:56.670 --> 01:58.670
If someone could
actually figure it out,

01:58.670 --> 02:00.130
that would change everything.

02:03.010 --> 02:05.350
Well, it's happening right now.

02:06.770 --> 02:08.940
Atmospheric refraction.

02:08.940 --> 02:11.320
Causes the light from the sun
to be distorted.

02:11.320 --> 02:15.750
The sun's already gone,
but we still see it.

02:15.750 --> 02:19.550
So it's here and not here
at the same time?

02:19.550 --> 02:22.970
Right now, we're looking
backwards in time,

02:22.970 --> 02:26.100
a moment stretched
beyond its normal limits.

02:26.100 --> 02:29.060
Imagine being given
extra time to consider,

02:29.060 --> 02:31.570
or reconsider what you're doing,

02:31.570 --> 02:33.570
the choices that you make.

02:33.570 --> 02:38.460
We could head off wars,
avoid accidents...

02:38.460 --> 02:41.130
I could not wear pink taffeta
to my senior prom.

02:41.130 --> 02:43.760
Time travel's not about
going back and forth.

02:43.760 --> 02:47.060
It's about staying
right where we are,

02:47.060 --> 02:49.730
about positioning
ourselves so that...

02:51.440 --> 02:53.530
we remain in the presence of
beauty.

02:56.740 --> 02:59.500
I'm Victor. Victor Stein.

03:00.960 --> 03:01.880
Janet.

03:06.260 --> 03:08.730
Do babies yawn?
Was he supposed to do that?

03:15.320 --> 03:16.620
Did you see?

03:19.410 --> 03:20.670
He's...

03:22.550 --> 03:24.090
He's...

03:24.090 --> 03:25.680
Everything.

03:25.680 --> 03:26.720
Yeah.

03:30.060 --> 03:31.270
I get it now.

03:32.570 --> 03:34.490
What everybody says.

03:34.490 --> 03:36.030
And what's that?

03:38.330 --> 03:40.330
This is the only thing
that matters.

03:43.710 --> 03:44.760
Just this.

